Current postal address - Line 1 - Inform the relevant field with the current postal address. The suburb/town/city, state/territory and postcode must be supplied in the separate fields as specified and MUST NOT be included in the first or second address line fields. The postal address must be provided in the 1st and 2nd address lines. It may not be necessary to use both lines. If the second line is not used then the field must be blank filled.

Postal address on previous return - Line 1 - Inform the relevant field with the postal address on the previous return. The suburb/town/city, state/territory and postcode must be supplied in the separate fields as specified and MUST NOT be included in the first or second address line fields. The current business address must be provided in the 1st and 2nd address lines. It may not be necessary to use both lines.

Do you expect to lodge an FBT return for future years?

Do you expect to lodge an FBT return for future years? - Inform the relevant field with the answer to the question. The employer does not need to lodge an FBT return if the fringe benefits taxable amount for the FBT year is nil. Answering False to this question will result in your FBT registration and any instalments being cancelled from this year onwards.
Hours taken to prepare and complete this form

Hours taken to prepare and complete this form - Inform the relevant field with the hours taken to prepare and complete this form. The ATO is committed to reducing the costs involved in complying with tax obligations. While the response to this question is voluntary, it will help the agency to monitor these costs as closely as possible. When completing this question, consider the time (rounded up to the nearest hour) spent: - reading the instructions; - collecting the necessary information to complete this return; - making any necessary calculations, and; - actually completing this return and/or putting the business tax affairs in order to give the information to the tax agent. Do not include the time the tax agent took to prepare and complete this return.

Number of employees receiving fringe benefits during the period 1 April 2007 to 31 March 2008

Number of employees receiving fringe benefits during the period 1 April 2007 to 31 March 2008 - Inform the relevant field with the total number of employees, and their associates, who received fringe benefits during the FBT year. This total should include any former or future employees, or their associates, who received fringe benefits during the FBT year.
Type 1 aggregate amount

Type 1 aggregate amount - Inform the relevant field with the Type 1 aggregate amount. A type 1 aggregate applies if the employer (or a member of the same GST group) are entitled to a GST credit for goods or services acquired in providing fringe benefits. GST affects the calculation of an employer's FBT liability. Where the benefit provider is entitled to a GST credit for goods or services acquired to provide fringe benefits, a higher gross-up rate (type 1) applies when calculating the FBT liability. The higher gross-up rate recovers the GST credit the benefit provider is entitled to.
Type 1 aggregate factored amount

Type 1 aggregate factored amount - Inform the relevant field with the Type 1 aggregate factored amount. Add together each employee's individual fringe benefits amount calculated in respect of those fringe benefits that are GST-creditable benefits (that is where the provider was entitled to a GST credit). Add any excluded fringe benefits that are GST-creditable benefits to this total amount. calculate the FBT liability using the formula: Type 1 aggregate fringe benefits amount * (FBT rate + GST rate ) / ((1 - FBT rate) * (1 + GST rate) * FBT rate)
Type 2 aggregate amount

Type 2 aggregate amount - Inform the relevant field with the Type 2 aggregate amount. Where there is no entitlement to a GST credit, the lower gross-up rate (type 2) applies. Type 2 fringe benefits are those for which the employer can't claim a GST credit because: - it is not entitled to (for example, you're not registered for GST), or - there are no GST credits available (that is the benefit is GST-free such as school fees, or input taxed, such as housing other than commercial accommodation).
Type 2 aggregate factored amount

Type 2 aggregate factored amount - Inform the relevant field with the Type 2 aggregate factored amount. Add together each employee's individual fringe benefits amount for those benefits that are not GST-creditable benefits (that is, where the provider did not pay GST, or a GST credit was not allowed when the benefits were acquired). Add any excluded fringe benefits that are not GST-creditable benefits to this total amount. Calculate the FBT liability using the formula: (Type 2 aggregate fringe benefits amount) * 1 / (1 - FBT rate)
Aggregate Non-exempt amount (hospitals, ambulances, public benevolent institutions and health promotion charities only)

Aggregate Non-exempt amount (hospitals, ambulances, public benevolent institutions and health promotion charities only) - Inform the relevant field with the aggregate non-exempt amount. Employers that are public benevolent institutions (PBIs), health promotion charities, public hospitals, non-profit hospitals or public ambulance services need to complete only the Aggregate non-exempt amount and not type 1 aggregate amount and type 2 aggregate amounts. Other employers including rebatable employers should leave this field blank.
Fringe benefits taxable amount (A + B) or C

Fringe benefits taxable amount (A + B) or C - Inform the relevant field with the Fringe benefits taxable amount using type 1 aggregate amount and item type 2 aggregate amount or aggregate non-exempt amount. This item must be completed even if the amount is nil.
Amount of tax payable

Amount of tax payable - Inform the relevant field with the amount of tax payable. This is the fringe benefits taxable amount multiplied by the current FBT rate. This item must be completed even if the amount is nil.

Aggregate non rebatable amount - Inform the relevant field with the aggregate non rebatable amount. This item applies only to rebatable employers. Rebatable employers are Certain non-government, non-profit organisations are eligible for a rebate for the amount of FBT that would otherwise be payable. If you are not a rebatable employer, leave this item blank.
Amount of rebate

Amount of rebate - Inform the relevant filed with the amount of rebate. Rebatable employers are certain non-government, non-profit organisations that are eligible for a rebate on the amount of FBT that would otherwise be payable If you are not a rebatable employer leave this item blank Formula 48% * (gross tax - aggregate non-rebatable amount) * rebatable days in year / total days in year
Payment due or credit due to you
Payment or credit due - Inform the relevant field with the payment or credit due.

Loans granted - Value of reductions - Inform the relevant field with the total amount by which benefits of that type have been reduced under the 'otherwise deductible' rule or other reductions.

Expense payments - Value of reductions - Inform the relevant field with the total amount by which benefits of that type have been reduced under the 'otherwise deductible' rule or other reductions, for example, in relation to in-house fringe benefits. The 'otherwise deductible' rule applies only if the recipients of the benefits are current employees and the employer obtains from them any necessary supporting documents such as declarations, receipts or invoices. The employer should obtain these before lodging the FBT return.

Employees receiving living-away-from-home allowance - Value of reductions - Inform the relevant field with the amount of reduction of taxable value of that particular benefit type. The exempt accommodation and increased food component amount are shown as reductions at 'Value of reductions'. The employer will need to obtain the necessary employee declarations to take advantage of any exempt accommodation and increased food components.

Sub - total (Amount of tax payable less Amount of rebate)

Sub - total - Inform the relevant field with the amount of tax payable less the amount of amount of rebate. If you are not a rebatable employer, this amount will be the same as the amount of tax payable.
Less instalment amounts reported on activity statements

Less instalment amounts reported on activity statements - Inform the relevant field with the Total the FBT instalment amounts reported on the employer's activity statement for the current FBT year and inform the total amount of less instalment amounts reported on activity statements. This amount will be credited against the employer's total current FBT liability. Don't include any amount paid in respect of penalties or another year's liability. If the employer has made a payment towards its current FBT liability as part of a tax agent lodgment agreement this amount can be included at this item. If the employer pays FBT by instalments the employer should lodge all of its activity statements for the FBT year ending 31 March of the current FBT year, including the March quarter prior to lodging the FBT return. This will enable the ATO to update the employer's FBT account. If the employer do not pay FBT by instalments then this field must be left blank.
